The paper deals with information-theoretic aspects of fingerprinting and group testing games, which are closely related to information theory and coding theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses attacks and defenses in these games, which falls under the scope of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The use of algorithms and decoding techniques suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) could also be a relevant sub-category. The paper also mentions multimedia fingerprinting, which could be classified under cs.MM (Multimedia). Finally, the paper deals with joint decoding, which is a topic in cs.SI (Signal Processing).
